[1] Brazil
- Brazil: Next Epicenter?
Date: 2 Jul 2020
Source: NY Times [edited]
https://www.nytimes.com/article/brazil-coronavirus-cases.html


Latin America became the epicenter of the coronavirus pandemic in late May 2020, largely driven by Brazil's ballooning caseload, as the number of infections in the United States and Europe fell.

In recent weeks, Brazil has reported upward of 1000 new deaths a day from Covid-19, the disease caused by the coronavirus, eclipsing the death toll in every country other than the United States. On 19 Jun 2020, the country reported 54 771 new cases, the largest one-day total for any country hit by the pandemic. If the trend lines hold, some epidemiologists project the death toll of the epidemic in Brazil could surpass that in the United States by late July 2020.

Even as the country's coronavirus crisis worsened in recent weeks, some major cities eased preventive measures in mid-June 2020. Shopping malls have begun to reopen in Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro. Beaches are starting to draw crowds again, even as some hospital systems are close to running out of intensive care beds.

Brazil declared a public health emergency in early March 2020, just a few days after the World Health Organization did. The Ministry of Health urged state officials to cancel public events and put social-distancing measures in place.

Some experts thought Brazil was well equipped to rise to the challenge, based on its track record during past public health emergencies. Brazil had months to study the responses of the 1st countries hit by the virus, and it has a public health care system that, while underfunded, provides robust coverage across the country.

The conflicting messages from the government, experts say, left Brazilians uncertain about the merits of isolation measures, which led to low compliance. That in turn led to Brazil's contagion rate being one of the highest in the world.

Brazil has struggled to import essential and lifesaving equipment, like coronavirus tests and ventilators. The lack of tests has made it difficult for officials to understand in real time where and how fast the virus is spreading. Experts believe Brazil's official coronavirus figures significantly undercount the scope of the problem.

Between 1 Jan - 6 Jun 2020, 23 171 people who were not diagnosed with the coronavirus died from acute respiratory infections, according to data released by Fiocruz, one of Brazil's state-run health research institutes. Experts believe most of them died from Covid-19.

Hospital systems have largely coped with the crush of patients, but the virus has taken a devastating toll on health care workers. Dozens of nurses and hospital technicians have died after contracting the virus at work.

Poor Brazilians who get sick are less likely to receive high quality health care. Although most public hospitals are operating near full capacity, several private hospitals have plenty of room to spare. The death rate in poorer cities has been substantially higher than the rate in rich ones.

There are some signs that the outbreak in Brazil is starting to stabilize. A study by the Imperial College London estimated that Brazil's contagion rate reached 1.05 this week, down from 2.8 in April 2020. The current rate means every 100 people who are contaminated infect another 105. The outbreak is considered to be under control when the contagion rate is below 1.

"The rise is not as exponential as it was previously," Michael Ryan, the World Health Organization's executive director, told reporters, but the disease can take off again."

