- EPICOVID19-BR: large Brazilian seroepidemiologic survey
Date: July 2020
Source: IBOPE Inteligencia [Brazilian Institute of Public Opinion and Statistics]
https://static.poder360.com.br/2020/07/epicovid19-resultados-2jul2020.pdf
[Powerpoint slide presentation, machine trans. from Portuguese, edited]

[Slide no.2] EPICOVID19-BR
• Largest epidemiological study in the world about coronavirus
• Number of people tested: 89,397
• Geographic coverage
• Three phases
- 1. May 14-21
- 2. 04-07 June
- 3. June 21-24
• Selection by lot

[3] Quick test
• Wondfo test (IgM and / or IgG)
• Previous validations
• Sensitivity 85%
• Specificity> 99.9%
• Finger punch
• Result in 15 minutes

[4] Research questions
1) Assess the proportion of the population with antibodies
2) Analyze the speed of infection expansion
3) Determine the percentage of infected without symptoms
4) Describe the most frequent symptoms
5) Estimate the lethality of the infection

[5-7] Results
[to answer research questions 1 and 2: graphs showing prevalence in Phase 1, 2, and 3]

[9] The most common symptoms
Smell / taste change, 62.9%
Headache, 62.2%
Fever, 56.2%
Cough, 53.1%
Body ache, 52.3%
Sore throat, 35.1%
Diarrhea, 29.3%
Difficulty breathing, 26.9%
Body shaking, 26.2%
Palpitation, 23.1%
Vomiting, 10.3%

[10] Asymptomatic
9% [pie chart]

[12] Lethality of infection
1.15% (1.05% -1.25%)
Numerator: Deaths by COVID-19 obtained from official statistics on June 20, in the 133 cities included in the survey
Denominator: Proportion of people with a positive result in the test (with correction for test validity and outline sample), multiplied by the population, in the 133 cities

[13] Research questions
6) Study differences between regions in Brazil
7) Estimate differences in the percentage of infected individuals according to sex, age, level
socioeconomic status and skin color
8) Quantify the difference between the number of reported cases and the total number of people
with antibodies
9) Assess intra-family transmission
10) Analyze adherence to social distance

[14] Geographic regions
[bar graphs showing differences in 5 different regions of Brazil, in each phase 1-2-3]

[16] Sex
[bar graphs showing differences in sex, in each phase 1-2-3]

[17] Age
[bar graphs showing differences in sex, in each phase 1-2-3]

[18] Socioeconomic level
[bar graphs showing differences in 5 socioeconomic levels, in each phase 1-2-3]

[20] Difference between the number of reported cases and the total number of people
with antibodies
Phase 1: 7x
Phase 2: 6x
Phase 3: 6x

[22] Intra-family transmission
39% positive
61% negative

[24] Social distance
[Bar graphs showing 3 levels of degree of adherence to social distancing, in Phases 1-2-3]

[25] Conclusions
• Epidemiological intelligence is essential
• Various epidemic curves (country, regions, states, cities)
• 53% and 23% increases between phases
• More mild symptomatic cases than asymptomatic
• Children are also infected, as well as adults
• More infection among the poorest
• 1 out of every 100 infected by the coronavirus dies
• Confirmation of the iceberg theory (6x)

