[2] Australia: Rise in Cases
Date: 4 Jul 2020
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-australia/australias-victoria-reports-108-new-coronavirus-cases-biggest-jump-since-march-idUSKCN24508A


Australia's 2nd most-populous state, Victoria, reported its largest jump in coronavirus cases since late March 2020 on Saturday [4 Jul 2020], forcing the expansion of stay-at-home orders to more Melbourne suburbs and the complete lockdown of 9 public housing towers.

The southeastern state recorded 108 new cases on Saturday [4 Jul 2020], up from 66 on Fri 3 Jul 2020 and more than 70 new cases in each of the previous 4 days.

"These numbers are a very real concern to all of us," Victorian Premier Daniel Andrews told a news conference.

The spike in Victoria is being closely watched as the rest of the country has reined in the virus that causes COVID-19.

Australia's most populated state, New South Wales, reported 6 new coronavirus cases on Saturday [4 Jul 2020], 5 of them returning travellers from overseas.

Overall, Australia has weathered the coronavirus pandemic much better than most other nations, with just over 8300 cases and 104 deaths so far.

The 9 towers in Melbourne consist of 1345 units, housing about 3000 residents. They will be locked down for at least 5 days, effective immediately, after many residents from those towers returned a positive COVID-19 test.

Police will be placed on each floor of the towers, and law enforcement authorities will also control access points.

"These are very challenging times," Premier Andrews added. "The alternative is that this gets right away from us, and we have not just 12 postcodes in lockdown but every postcode locked down. I don't want to get to that."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of cases has risen slowly in Australia since the 1st case was reported on 15 Feb 2020. Imposing restrictions in identified hotspots is an essential feature to check COVID-19 transmission, but this has to be coupled with robust testing to confirm and isolate cases and to identify contacts and implement quarantine measures.

Important information for Victorians can be accessed at https://www.vic.gov.au/coronavirus. - Mod.UBA]

