Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update (please note that there has been a consistent weekend reporting artifact since the presentation of these data began):
----------------------------------
The Americas region reported 61.1% of the global newly reported cases and 66.1% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. The USA reported 41.0% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, and Brazil reported 37.1%, Mexico 5.2%, Colombia 3.2%, Peru and Chile at 2.7% each, and Argentina 2.1%. The same 5 countries remained at the top; the USA and Brazil are usually numbers 1 and 2; while they vary for which of the 2 positions they hold, this week the USA has dominated with the proportion represented by Brazil decreasing. Other countries are continuing to increase their proportional representation within the region such as Mexico, Colombia, Peru, and periodically Chile, Ecuador, and Argentina.

The European region reported 9.3% of the global newly reported cases and 11.0% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 33.6% of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Kazakhstan 8.3%, Turkey 5.9%, Israel 5.7%, Ukraine 4.6%, Sweden 3.9%, Armenia 2.9%, the UK 2.6%, France and Spain at 2.3%, Romania and Germany at 2.1% each. The proportion of cases represented by Russia continues to decrease. Armenia, Azerbaijan, Israel, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, and Ukraine are prominent in countries noted to have resurgence in Europe.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 9.3% of the global newly reported cases and 9.6% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 20.9% of the regional newly reported cases followed by Pakistan at 16.8%, Iran 12.8%, Iraq 11.5%, Qatar 8.3 %, Egypt 7.0%, Oman 6.8%, and Kuwait 4.1%. Multiple countries are very active in the region, the same countries with some changes in the order since yesterday (3 Jul 2020). Qatar moved to number 5 in daily case numbers.

The African region reported 5.9% of the global newly reported cases and 2.7% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 71.8% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ghana 6.0%, Nigeria 3.6%, Algeria 3.3%, Cote d'Ivoire 2.2%, and Kenya 1.9. South Africa and Nigeria are usually numbers 1 and 2 [Ghana is number 2 in the last 24 hours], and other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day. Of note is that South Africa is now reporting over 8000 cases in a day.

The Western Pacific region reported 1.1% of the global newly reported cases and 0.15% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 68.0% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Australia 11.2%, Japan 9.5%, Singapore 7.5%, South Korea 2.7%, and China 0.40%. The Philippines is consistently reporting the highest number of cases while today [4 Jul 2020], Australia surpassed Japan for the number 2 slot. Other countries, including South Korea, Malaysia, and Australia, vary in daily reporting.

The South East Asia region reported 13.2% of the global newly reported cases and 10.4% of global deaths. India reported 81.5% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 11.1%, Indonesia 4.6%, and Nepal 2.6%, the same countries, same order as in previous days, with India continuing to be the driving force in the regional growth in cases.

Impression: The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis, followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe and the Eastern Mediterranean alternating on a daily basis of their order, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily case load of all of the regions. The Africa region is slowing increasing their representation in terms of increased case reporting.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 4 Jul 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South-East Asia, in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting.

The WHO Timeline of WHO's response to COVID-19 [last updated 30 Jun 2020] has also acknowledged ProMED's earliest alert generated on the undiagnosed confirmed pneumonia cases: "WHO's Epidemic Intelligence from Open Sources (EIOS) platform also picked up a media report on ProMED (a program of the International Society for Infectious Diseases) about the same cluster of cases of "pneumonia of unknown cause" in Wuhan" on 31 Dec 2019. - Mod.UBA]

