Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of reported cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 11 190 678, with reports of cases by 217 countries and territories worldwide. The total case numbers crossed the 11 million mark in the last 24 hours. The global case count rose by 1.6% in the past 24 hours. The USA, with more than 2.91 million confirmed cases, now represents 25.6% of the global cases of COVID-19, and Brazil with more than 1.54 million cases represents 13.7% of the global cases of COVID-19. Other countries such as Chile, Peru, Mexico, India, Saudi Arabia, South Africa, and Pakistan are reporting increased numbers of new and cumulative cases as well. If one tallies the total cumulative case counts for the top 5 countries (USA, Brazil, Russia, India, and Spain), they represent over half of the total cases reported globally (53.9%). A global total of 533 388 deaths have been reported, an increase of 5077 deaths in the past 24 hours.

A reminder that in the absence of well-developed contact-tracing activities with testing of asymptomatic and mildly ill contacts, numbers of SARS-CoV-2 virus infections are significantly underreported: actual numbers may be 10-20 times larger. There are also individuals who stay at home throughout their illness, sometimes, unfortunately, dying at home, who are never officially confirmed as infected with the SARS-CoV-2 virus. These data are presented to provide relative indicators of the situations in each of the countries and comparisons between countries and regions of the world.

In descending rank order, the USA is number 1 for cumulative confirmed cases of COVID-19, followed by Brazil, Russia, India, Spain, Peru, Chile, the UK, Mexico, and Italy at number 10. China remains at number 22. In descending rank order, the USA is number 1 for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by India, Brazil, Mexico, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Pakistan, Bangladesh, and Iran. Kazakhstan has been replaced on the top 10 and is now number 17 on this list, reflecting continued increase in transmission in the country. All countries that are currently experiencing major community-based transmission and considered global hot spots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases went from 2449 to 24 969.

The top 20 countries in terms of cumulative cases include 7 from the European region, 7 from the Americas region, 3 from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 2 from the South-East Asia region, and 1 from the African region unchanged for the past 3 days. There are no countries from the Western Pacific region. The top 20 countries in terms of numbers of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours include 8 from the Americas region, 6 from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 3 from the South East Asia region, 2 from the European region, 1 from the African region (an increase of 1 in the Americas region and a dropping off of the 1 in the Western Pacific region). This listing very much reflects the "hot spots" in terms of countries and regions with ongoing high transmission of the SARS-CoV-2 virus.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts. - Mod.UBA]
